{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539187"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:38:15+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:38:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16480"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16480"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.21,0.33,0.12,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9171"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65501"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9171"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16480"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50940"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"115"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"3354"},{"type":"tags","id":"3416"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21777"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43944"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65501"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-month history of progressive abdominal bloating, excessive flatulence, and loose stools. Her symptoms worsen after meals and she has lost 3 kg of weight. She has a history of systemic sclerosis and type 2 diabetes mellitus. Her medications include pantoprazole, nifedipine and metformin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her abdomen is soft and mildly distended with generalised tenderness but no masses. Stool microscopy and culture are negative for pathogens, and faecal calprotectin is 45 \u00b5g/g (\u0026lt;50).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Irritable bowel syndrome","Pancreatic insufficiency","Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth","Inflammatory bowel disease","Colorectal cancer"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of small intestinal bacterial overgrowth (SIBO). The key clinical features are chronic bloating, diarrhoea, and weight loss, along with multiple predisposing risk factors including systemic sclerosis and diabetes mellitus. Long term proton pump inhibitor use may lead to gastric hypochlorhydria, an additional risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall intestinal bacterial overgrowth\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when colonic bacteria excessively proliferate in the small intestine. This leads to malabsorption of nutrients, bacterial fermentation of carbohydrates causing bloating and flatulence, and diarrhoea. In severe cases, patients may develop a macrocytic anaemia and B12 deficiency due to bacterial activity. Factors which increase the risk of SIBO include impaired small intestinal motility (seen in systemic sclerosis and diabetes mellitus) and anatomic abnormalities of the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIrritable bowel syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar symptoms of bloating and altered bowel habits. However, weight loss is not typically a feature, and the presence of multiple risk factors for SIBO makes this diagnosis less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreatic insufficiency\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with steatorrhoea (foul-smelling, floating stools), epigastric pain, and weight loss. While it can cause malabsorption, there is no history of alcohol use, pancreatitis, or severe epigastric pain to suggest this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInflammatory bowel disease\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with elevated faecal calprotectin, and often with other features such as blood in stool, fever, or extraintestinal manifestations. The normal faecal calprotectin makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColorectal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in older patients with altered bowel habits, rectal bleeding, or iron deficiency anaemia. The predominant symptoms of bloating and the normal faecal calprotectin make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiagnosis of SIBO can be confirmed with carbohydrate breath testing or duodenal aspirate culture, though many clinicians treat empirically with antibiotics (typically rifaximin) when the clinical picture is highly suggestive. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth occurs when colonic bacteria colonise and excessively proliferate in the small bowel, leading to malabsorption and bloating.","Risk factors include disorders of intestinal motility (such as systemic sclerosis and diabetes) and anatomy"],"references":["Pimentel M, Saad RJ, Long MD, Rao SSC. ACG Clinical Guideline: Small Intestinal Bacterial Overgrowth. Official journal of the American College of Gastroenterology | ACG [Internet]. 2020;115(2). Available from: https://journals.lww.com/ajg/fulltext/2020/02000/acg_clinical_guideline__small_intestinal_bacterial.9.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16480"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T14:48:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-26T14:50:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9171"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65501"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/115"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Systemic sclerosis","syno